- Saunders saturation calls
    - format: one entry per chapter when first-pass extraction completes
    - entry shape:
        - what came out of this chapter
        - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - why those did not make it
        - decision: saturated | re-sweep needed

- Chapter 1: Front Matter (copyright, table of contents, epigraph)
    - what came out: nothing
    - what didn't make the gate: not applicable. The chapter is bibliographic metadata (copyright, TOC, an epigraph). It contains no teaching content from which moves could be extracted.
    - why: the chapter is structural front matter, not authorial argument or demonstration.
    - decision: saturated (vacuously, with zero skills)

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - what came out: the-basic-drill, ask-strategic-not-interpretive, is-it-helping
    - what didn't make the gate:
        - keeping a small set of touchstone stories as a high bar (autobiographical aside, no concrete action)
        - workbook stance, going deeper than a first read allows (folded into the-basic-drill, which is the actual mechanism)
        - reading from the reader's experience as such (parent-context lens already captured in _book.md)
        - iconic space, resistance literature, rhetorical trial balloons (parent-context vocabulary already in _book.md; the only one that yielded an atomic move was the trial-balloon disposition, promoted as is-it-helping)
    - why: the chapter is mostly framing, lens-setting, and vocabulary already absorbed into _book.md as parent context. The three skills that survive each name a concrete reader/writer/teacher action with an observable signal and a recognizable failure mode, distinct from the lens itself. The dropped items are either vague or already covered.
    - decision: saturated

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - what came out: page-break-diagnostic, hollywood-version, cornfeld-principle, ritual-banality-avoidance, two-version-comparison, increasing-specification, truncation-test
    - what didn't make the gate:
        - bowling pins / juggler metaphor for tracking expectations (folded into page-break-diagnostic, which is the procedural form Saunders gives this idea)
        - structure as call-and-response between questions raised and answers supplied (folded into page-break-diagnostic for the same reason)
        - cross-painting characters with contradictory traits (folded into increasing-specification as one technique within the larger move)
        - variation against stasis when a beat repeats (dropped: action "vary it" too vague, no concrete signal that distinguishes good variation)
        - the motorcycle-and-sidecar metaphor for reader-writer closeness (dropped: evocative model rather than procedure, no concrete action or measurable signal)
        - "ruthless efficiency principle" as standalone (overlaps too tightly with cornfeld-principle, which is the procedural test the REP demands; folded by reference within cornfeld-principle's framing)
        - story-as-system-for-energy-transfer (dropped: a powerful image with no procedural form independent of the moves already promoted, especially ritual-banality-avoidance and truncation-test)
        - "Is it story yet?" as a slogan (folded into truncation-test, which is the actual mechanism for answering it)
    - why: this chapter is unusually rich because Saunders teaches by demonstrating multiple procedural moves in sequence on a single Chekhov story. Many candidates surfaced; the gate forced consolidation. Each promoted skill names a distinct situation and a distinct procedure, with no two doing the same work at different specificity. The dropped items are either evocative metaphors without independent procedural form (motorcycle/sidecar, energy transfer) or restatements of moves already promoted under sharper names (REP under cornfeld-principle, "Is it story yet?" under truncation-test, structure-as-call-and-response under page-break-diagnostic). Seven skills is at the upper end of the chapter's length budget but the chapter genuinely does the work to support each one.
    - decision: saturated

- Chapter 4: Afterthought #1
    - what came out: take-responsibility-for-every-element
    - what didn't make the gate:
        - the "Cat in the Rain" classroom recipe (folded: it is page-break-diagnostic + truncation-test packaged for a different story; no new procedural content)
        - the one-paragraph review of criticism as moment-by-moment noticing-and-articulating (folded into the-basic-drill, which is the procedural form)
        - Hemingway's "shockproof shit detector" (folded into the-basic-drill: a vivid name for the same trust-your-honest-reaction stance)
        - "an artist takes responsibility" as a standalone disposition (folded into take-responsibility-for-every-element, which operationalizes it)
    - why: this Afterthought is mostly recap and repackaging of the previous chapter's moves, plus one genuinely new application of the line-by-line lens to a film sequence. The recap content folds cleanly into existing skills under sharper procedural names. The Bicycle Thieves passage introduces something the prior chapter does not have a procedure for: an audit at the within-frame level (every element in a composed unit), which is finer-grained than cornfeld-principle (scene-level) and different in shape from two-version-comparison (audit what is there vs imagine what is not). The rest of the Afterthought is rhetorical reinforcement of the parent-context lens.
    - decision: saturated

- Chapter 5: The Singers (Turgenev source story)
    - what came out: none
    - what didn't make the gate: the chapter is Turgenev's story itself, not Saunders teaching. Visible structural features include the long village/pub framing before the action, the extended character portraits inserted between the buildup and the contest, the contrast between the contractor's technically dazzling first performance and Yashka's transcendent second performance, the narrator's choice to exit at the peak and return to find a deflated drunken aftermath, and the closing "Antropka!" call fading across the valley. Each is a teachable feature in principle, but the procedural form (action, observable signal, named failure mode) cannot be articulated honestly from the story alone without anticipating Chapter 6's commentary, which is out of scope for this pass.
    - why: source stories supply scenarios; teaching moves come from Saunders's commentary chapters. The right place for moves about narrative structure, character portraiture, and what Saunders calls "the heart of the story" is Chapter 6, which uses this story as its data.
    - decision: saturated

- Chapter 6: The Heart of the Story
    - what came out: track-non-normative-excesses, heart-of-the-story, panel-of-judges, holding-up-against-the-heart, energy-not-aspiration
    - what didn't make the gate:
        - "establishings, stabilizations, alterations" as a vocabulary for beat-tracking (folded into page-break-diagnostic; same beat-tracking the three-question protocol surfaces, restated in different terms)
        - "specificity makes character" and the contest-stakes formulation (A and B must stand for something) (folded into increasing-specification, which is the procedural form; Ch 6 sharpens its trigger to contest-shaped stories whose outcomes feel arbitrary)
        - the "20% then 10% more" cutting assignment (dropped: a teaching exercise without an observable signal that distinguishes good cutting from bad; the underlying ability "touch" is named but not operationalized; cornfeld-principle and take-responsibility-for-every-element supply the procedural tests for what to cut. Note: Appendix A is itself a cutting exercise and may surface a procedural skill on its own ground.)
        - "letting it stand" / final approval by sending out (folded into take-responsibility-for-every-element as its terminal stopping rule: the doorway image gives the audit's stop condition)
        - "Hollywood version" of "The Singers" (folded into hollywood-version as a second worked instance; Saunders here also clarifies that the Hollywood version is distinct from "the heart of the story," which is the new skill promoted)
    - why: this chapter is dense with new procedural moves because Saunders is teaching at the level of macro-structure (heart of story, panel of judges, holding up against), reader-side cataloging (TICHN), and writer-self-discovery (energy/voice). Five skills emerged. The folds are real refinements (Ch 6 supplies sharper triggers and worked instances for moves already promoted) rather than near-duplicates. The single drop is a classroom assignment that does not have the gate's procedural shape. Particular care was needed on heart-of-the-story vs. hollywood-version: Saunders himself distinguishes these in line 1690 ("The Hollywood version of 'The Singers' would be something like: 'Two men have a singing contest in a Russian pub. One wins, one loses.'" — versus "The heart of 'The Singers' is, of course, the singing contest"). The Hollywood version is the one-sentence story-shape used as a constraint on what the story is trying to be; the heart is the central scene/event the rest must route energy to. They fire in different revision moments and produce different decisions, so they are kept apart, with related: links to be set during finalization.
    - decision: saturated

- Chapter 7: Afterthought #2
    - what came out: iterative-preference-revision, respect-the-reader-cut
    - what didn't make the gate:
        - the line-level "Bob was an asshole" specification revision (folded into increasing-specification: same move applied to a single sentence rather than to a character introduction; Ch 7 sharpens the trigger to "a sentence that states a verdict instead of rendering the moment that produced it" and supplies the moral-ethical side-effect framing)
        - the disposition of trusting felt impulse during revision because each pass can revert the previous one (folded into iterative-preference-revision: this is the disposition the skill operationalizes, not a separate move)
        - the Stan-and-model-railroad image of art beginning in the instant of intuitive preference (folded into iterative-preference-revision: the chapter's opening illustration of the same move the skill operationalizes)
        - the apartment-redecoration analogy and the seed-crystal image for why iteration produces self-revealing work (folded into iterative-preference-revision: the analogies that motivate the procedure)
    - why: this Afterthought is autobiographical reflection on Saunders's own revision method. Two genuinely procedural moves emerge that the prior chapters do not give a procedure for: the iterative micro-revision practice driven by felt preference (the P/N meter), and the specific cutting test where an intelligent reader would supply what is being explained. The first is distinct from existing skills because no prior skill is about the act of self-revision itself (page-break-diagnostic surfaces expectations; cornfeld-principle and take-responsibility-for-every-element audit elements for function; truncation-test isolates ending work; none names the iterative reading-and-reacting practice). The second is distinct from take-responsibility-for-every-element because the test is not "does this element have a function" but "would the reader supply this for themselves from what is already on the page." The folds are real: the Bob example IS increasing-specification at sentence rather than character scope; the apartment, seed-crystal, and Stan images are illustrations of the iterative method, not separate moves. Two skills sits at the upper end of an Afterthought's length budget but the chapter genuinely supplies both procedures with worked examples.
    - decision: saturated
